SIMPLE: typhon
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Typhon
<hw>Ty"phon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/, and <?/. See
<er>Typhoon</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Class. Mythol.)</fld> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>According to Hesiod, the son of Typhoeus, and father of the winds,
but later identified with him.</def> <-- father of Cerberus, the
Chimera, and the Sphinx -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ By modern writers, <xex>Typhon</xex> is identified with
the Egyptian Set, who represents physical evil. <rj><au>Encyc.
Brit.</au></rj> </note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A violent whirlwind; a typhoon.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The circling <qex>typhon</qex> whirled from point to point.</q>
<rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Typhoon</ent>⟦br⟧
